This is a thing I created recently to prevent a reoccurrence of my friend losing his glasses whilst jet skiing. Basically, he stacked and his glasses sank to the bottom of the ocean! This is a floaty device that he can attach to the strap that holds his glasses on.

Buoyancy is the upward force that an object feels from the water and when compared to the weight of the object. It is what makes an object float, sink, or remain neutrally buoyant in the water.

When an object floats, the upward buoyant force exerted by the water is greater than the downward force of the weight of the object. You can also understand this concept with numbers. If an object’s density is less than water’s density (1 g/cm³), it will float.

Perhaps this is something you could use for a similar situation!

This is a 66mm wheel for a Tamiya 3mm hex shaft. I reused some silicone rubber bracelets (the green bands) as tires. In fact, that was the whole purpose -- to make a useful wheel with those bracelets. The circumference is about 210 mm.

I printed in PLA. Note that the hex opening is 3.3mm on paper. It was still a tight fit. Recommend 20% or more infill.

I used Sketchup because I found good 3d models of the tamiya gearboxes on 3dwarehouse.

I made this as a commissioned piece for a cosplay costume back in December. After talking with my client on it we have decided to release it to Thingiverse.

Notes:

In total 19 pieces, printed it in PLA filament.
Print speeds between 40 and 60 mm/s for best results.
20% infill on all but the smallest pieces (which for size reason are printed at 100%)

Total parts print time for me was 19.25 hours
using about 85m of filament (slightly less than a quarter kilo.)

I designed this lightsaber replica off of screen captures for the Star Wars Rebels animated series on Disney XD. I worked from the stylized proportions and scale and did a lot of eyeballing to get the correct look and feel, I still feel like it is a bit long and maybe too fat but I am pleased with the results. I used simple polygonal modeling in 3ds Max, and ProBooleans to cut the pieces, a general tolerance between pieces was made to be about 0.2 to 0.4 mm and each interface between pieces is unique so it can only be assembled one way.

Files Labels with 00 are inlays and detail pieces.
Print one of each of stl files provided except for 00c-Kanan-MagneticChoke_x2.stl wihich requires two copies to be printed and 00e-Kanan-GribRib_x7.stl which needs seven copies.

Assemble by gluing Pommel - Haft Bottom - haft set pin - Haft Top - Magnetic Stabilizer - Neck Bell - Blade Emitter together. After gluing install the grip ribs and face, glue. Finally install the rest where they fit.

Grip face my need some alteration after printing for the emitter trigger to fit right, this area has an unfortunately tight tolerance.

title: Water Rocket (Bottle Rocket) Adapter With Fins

description.text: This is a derivative of my 2 Liter bottle to 1/4 NPT adapter with reasonably sturdy little fins. The adapter is designed to let you quickly turn an ordinary house hold pop (soda) bottle into a projectile by adding water and air pressure. the 1/4 NPT quick disconnect gives you a simple and easy way to add air pressure and also works as a launch mechanism when you release the collar.
Please see the parent of this item for instructions, that way I can just make corrections there as I intend to make several derivatives.

comments.text: There is an easier and safer way to do these.. I'll do a remix when i have time.. we made these all the time when i was a kid BUT using the quick release metal piece not only adds weight at the rear where you don't want it, but means you have to have your hands there to release it.. OK the solution is to use the rubber schraeder valve from a tubeless car tyre.. doesn't actually matter if it's new or been cut away by a tyre depot.. what you have is a schraeder car valve in a rubber body with a smooth bulb at the end where it is usually fitted to a car wheel.. as kids we used old style fairy liquid washing up bottles as they had a very odd-sized neck that was an exact TIGHT fit to the valve bulb..ALL modern pop bottles are the same and too big to fit direct onto the valve.. just add a little water, attach you bicycle pump with an extension hose, point the bottle at the sky with some kind of support and pump till the pressure blows it off the rubber bulb.. you just need to reprint this with a smooth bore at the rear of the correct size to fit the valve stem, tighter tolerances will mean more pressure before it blows.. too much and the bottle will blow first.. the amount of water is critical too, more doesn't simply mean more thrust..
comments.author: gizmatron

comments.text: This is the second round of these that I have printed, a couple notes, you are going to need some sort of rubber seal for the bottle side and teflon tape for the air hose end.   I fired the first one off using only air and I ended up breaking a fin off.  I feel this is due to printing with only 20% infill. After the fin broke air was able to escape though where it broke.  So I decided to print 3 more with %100 infill and see where that takes me.

comments.text: I had an amazing time in high school one time doing something like this with a friend. We melted a smooth hole in some bottle caps and placed them over an aluminum tube we had connected to an air compressor. When we opened the valve (very fast blow-gun valve) it would presurise the bottle as it was coming off. Worked very well. We played around with more advanced stuff - a small clump of clay inside the bottle had an interesting effect. The tube kept the clay off the hole initially, so the bottle would still shoot off the tube and a bit of water would still shoot out to propel it upward. But then in the middle of the flight, while it was still partially pressurized, the clay would find the hole and plug it. The bottle would be in free flight for a bit while the clay was stuck in the hole, but eventually the pressure would shoot the clay out, and the remaining water and air would propel the bottle again. We had succeeded in literally making a two stage water bottle rocket with just a tube, compressor, and some clay! It was lots and lots of fun - the bottle would shoot up about 30 feet before stopping, then it would tumble in the air and eventually shoot off in a random direction. It was surprisingly repeatable, and we were able to vary the amount of clay to alter the timing. We eventually got it to the point where the bottle would come almost all the way back to the ground before the secondary "stage" fired. So much fun! It might be possible to 3D print a more reliable staging mechanism, though I'm not sure what that would look like!
comments.author: tlalexander

This is a 3D model of a section of the nave of a Gothic church. 
I based the height to width ratio on the golden section,and the design of the arches on the basic Gothic proportions, so nothing very new. I hope to add the side alleys and some flying buttresses in a later version.
The only clever trick is the use of little cross-shaped pieces to hold the two parts of the pillars together, one at the base, and one at the top, resting on a little shelf. Since the pillar parts that slot into each other are rather long, you need this trick to keep them from sliding side to side.

I don't have a laser, so I've never actually made this thing. [Edit: but I have made a smaller variant which assembled just fine, see below] I designed it in Sketchup, which worked well to see how pieces work together.
I think it fits together fine (if made from a 12"x12" piece of 1/4" thick acrylic or plywood) but I don't know how to calculate the kerf on the cuts... so this may need some adjustments to cut properly. Sorry for any waste of time and material... :-(
As for assembly, you will need to make at least two sets of parts to make a single nave section (four pillars and all the attendant arches). If you make more, you will notice that you are making more pillars than you need, so there will be some waste.
The pillars pieces slot into each other, and the cross pieces slide over the X thus formed and rest on the little shelf at the bottom.
Same idea at the top of the pillar, just pick a cross piece with the diagonal slots. The arch pieces should drop into the top cross piece, and there are little connector parts to join the arch halves at the top, like keystones.
Refer to the assembled pix for guidance, it should be relatively easy to figure out.

This is a simple bezel for the GDM 1602K as sold by Sparkfun with the serial adapter mounted on the rear: http://www.sparkfun.com/commerce/advanced_search_result.php?keywords=gdm+1602k In my current application I just glue it down, but I'm working on a newer version that can use different mounting styles. The split version is especially for MakerBot Cupcake users. To get the pieces to line up (and stay together), use some leftover 3mm ABS in the holes and ABS cement to hold it all together.

The single piece is pretty difficult to print on a MakerBot Cupcake without a heated platform, but it can be done if you have your 'Bot properly tweaked.
The split piece prints just fine on my stock Cupcake.
All of these are very slightly oversize to account for ABS shrinkage.  If you're using a commercial printer it might print out a wee bit too big.

title: Wormscrew for Hitachi C10FL Table Saw Blade Height Adjustment

description.text:
This is a replacement for the blade height adjustment worm screw on a Hitachi C10FL table saw.  The worm screw part no is 726713.  
You can buy this from Hitachi as a replacement part, and probably should.  However I needed my saw back in service immediately, so this is an emergency replacement.

I printed mine in PLA at 100% infill on a Makerbot Replicator, using both raft and support on MakerWare. Cleaning the support material from the threads is a bit tedious. I did not find it possible to get particularly smooth gear faces because of the support remnants, but that has not been a problem. I've made a couple of minor adjustments to the design after printing and installing the part - the shaft hole was too snug, and the overall part was slightly too long. I was able to fit it, but have tweaked these files based on that experience. You may need to refine those dimensions further. The action of the printed part is very smooth, certainly feels as good as the original, and is holding up fine under use so far. This worm screw takes a fairly heavy load, so I have no idea how long this part will last. If it were to break while the saw is cutting there is a chance that the lift imparted by the blade on whatever you are cutting could cause the blade to rise, so use at your own risk. In my own experience, when the original broke, the blade dropped down into the table. The thread STL was separately generated using the attached python scripts and imported into the openscad file. My initial attempt to produce the thread entirely using CSG in openscad resulted in unusably slow generation time. The hexagonal recess in the bottom end (not visible in the photos) does NOT appear to serve a purpose as far as I can tell. I copied it from the original, and assumed there was some sort of nut that needed to be recessed into it, but upon reassembly I found that end sits against a flat collar. If I print again I will remove it by commenting out the reference to nutRecess at the end of wormscrew.scad.

The Ring-A-Thing is a modular ring-building kit that will allow you to press-fit a small cube magnet into the base and glue a washer to the bottom of each design you make, allowing you to switch out designs on your printed ring.
It's parametric to finger diameter in mm, but I haven't yet figured out how to keep the diameter of the inset on the top of the ring stable for all ring sizes, so that you don't have to scale your designs.  
I'm also going to see if I can come up with a better way of attaching the designs than the 3mm magnets, which won't fit inside smaller ring sizes.
Once those two issues are figured out, this project will be a go!

1: Open up OpenSCAD file. It's parametric. Measure the diameter of your intended finger in mm, add a mm for clearance, and type it in. F6 render, export new STL. Print.
2: Press-fit 3mm magnet into hole in ring.
3: Print design disc(s).
4: Glue design disc to washer.
5: Place disc into ring, where it will click into place.
6: To change designs, get a small screwdriver and pry up one side of disc until it comes loose. Place new design into ring.
7: Enjoy.

description.text:
I had issues with printing the Bottom cover from the original.
The issues was that my slicer insists, to print a single perimeters of alle the holes before filling the rest of the bottom. This resulted (many times) in failed prints, since the perimeters of the holes did not adhere well on its own on the bed, and ended up getting dragged with the nozzle creating quite a mess.

My solution was to add a solid 0.2mm bottom layer to the whole case, including a fixed Brim, thus having a better chance to print the holes, without issues.
See the pictures for reference.

This thing is utterly useless. I would advise that you print it.

A lot of earbud wrappers still fit only the older iPhone/iPod/iPad earphones. I needed one for my iPhone 5 buds which have a volume switch/mic on the cord. So it had to wrap at very particular lengths of the wire.  
This one hugs the heads of the buds, keeps the stalks inside, allows you to wrap the wire nicely, and has a clip for the jack to hold it all together.  
PLEASE NOTE: The original model had two connected, solid shapes, and some printers don't like that. This model is a single, watertight model, much better for almost all printers.   
I hope you like it.  
PLEASE NOTE: A PERSON IS SELLING THESE ON ETSY AS HIS OWN DESIGN. IT IS NOT. PLEASE DO NOT PURCHASE FROM THAT SELLER.  
This is my design, carefully iterated on until it works perfectly.

I started with cardboard to get the desired length so the microphone/volume switch wouldn't end up where you'd want wire to bend. Then I printed a test, changed some values to better fit the bud shafts, and added a jack clip.

Update:
Based on danzca6's comment I put more effort into this. Now you can mark 90, 100, and 110mm. See it's good to voice all opinions! :)

It's so hard to get my calibers into the printer to mark off exactly 100 mm for before you tell your printer to extrude exactly 100mm of filament for calibration. so... Here you go.
Just hold the bar in place and mark with a marker then on your controller move the Extruder axis 100 mm and adjust CONTROL/MOTION/"Esteps/mm"

If you extruded too little bump the number up
If you extruded too much bump the number down

MAKE SURE YOU MEASURE THE EXTRUDED PART to be sure it is 100mm. Remember that If your calibrating your extruder, you make have reason to believe that it's not right!

Example I had 9.25 mm left and setting was 728.0 I moved it to 745.0 to get my perfect 100 mm extruded.

To get the numbers to print in Cura you will need to use a .25 mm nozzle.
Using a .4 nozzle all prints ok but the numbers are not printed.

** Expect to have to re-figure your Z Offset if an Esteps/mm setting is changed.

remixed_from.title: P3Steel - Prusa i3 3mm Steel Laser cut (aka Leonardo)

description.text:
Irobri's P3Steel v2.01 redesigned by Paciente8159 (v2.2)

This a redesign of irobri's near perfect P3Steel 3mm steel laser cut v2.01 3D printer
I actually have one (and I love it) an these changes reflect some of the things I would like mine to have. It was also changed with Diamond Head hot end in mind :-)

This is still a work in progress so future changes may occur.

For now this is what I've redesigned:
17-03-2016 Update

  • Holes to mount the RAMPS vertically

Base version

  • Larger holes the the main frame similar to v4 of the P3Steel frame to reduce weight and lower production costs (number and distance of cuts)
  • Slightly enlarged holes for the z stepper cables
  • Added clearance in the main frame cut to let the Y axis belt holder pass
  • Added cuts in the main frame to install up to 3 bowden extruders (cold end)
  • En longed side cuts to accommodate different power supplies
  • Reduced diameter of the holes for the Z axis smooth rods to prevent loosen linear rails
  • Changed Y axis idler piece to use F604ZZ bearing and re-centered the holes to allow a perfect and parallel line up of the Y belt
  • Simplified and removed several cuts on the triangular side and front and back plates to reduce production costs
  • Added support structure in a way that can accommodate 3 spools of filament using and M8 threaded rod and printed spool holders that are designed around common 608ZZ bearings (skate bearings)
  • Removed screw insert in the between the main frame and the side triangles (in the middle) to reduce the possibility of undesired hit's

These were the main changes.
Future changes may follow.

This is a tool for the Replicator 2X to help hold the extruder heaters in place while unscrewing the nozzle.  
The only way I have found to remove the nozzles without turning the heater itself and damaging the wires is by first bracing the cylindrical heater cartridges on the back side of the heater block.  
This tool does just that:  it prevents the heaters from twisting while unscrewing the extruder nozzles by bracing them against the carriage itself.  Just slide it up into place on the back side of the heaters between the belt and break the nozzles loose with a small (7mm seems to fit) wrench.  
NOTE:  DO NOT USE WITH THE HEATERS ON OR IT WILL MELT!!!!

comments.text: I use my 2X commercially, and it has over 4K hours on it. I need to either clean or replace a nozzle about once a month it seems. No more removing the heating blocks and re-levelling, or trying to hold them in place and wrecking the ceramic insulation (which MBI doesn't sell separately, the jerks). Great tool. Thanks!

description.text:
This is my first attempt at a remix. I haven't had a chance to print it yet, so I'm not sure how it will turn out. It will need support to bed. The wings should move. Good Luck

UPDATE 3-13-2016: Version 2 = A total redo of the wing hinges and a much larger tolerance.

UPDATE 3-9-2016: I've printed It on a Monoprice IIIP/Wanhao Duplicator I3

PLA+ from ESUN,
.15 layer height
40mm/sec
10 infill

Looks great!! has very tight tolerances on the wings - Be careful when unfolding them. I may change that at a later date.

Printer:

Monoprice II3/Wanhao Duplicator I3

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

20

Notes:

If you choose to print this before I do, Please let me know how it turns out. And a special thanks to HanShot1st for doing the wonderful ground work.
